description:
Less than 24 hours after AI171 went down - a large number of conspiracy theorists have sprung up and they are having a good time testing their theories. But for a crash of this magnitude - you need serious experts to weigh in and wait for the Black Box data before coming to any conclusion. 

However to put conspiracy theorists at bay - here are 7 things that the investigators will have to look into - to solve this riddle. It could be mechanical - but there is ONE probability - that is staring us in the face and its not pretty. 

The kind of global shock this crash has generated is not funny - understandable though - because for the first time you have a 787 hull loss .... here is further reading on the state of Indian Aviation and what global experts are thinking about this crash -

comments.text:
was Overloaded 
		 Flaps extended (beyond takeoff phase)
		 Landing gear left down
		 High temperature
		 Full fuel tanks

Overloaded
Exceeds lift capability; may not take off at all
Flaps extended
Helps lift at low speed but massively increases drag at higher speeds
Gear down
Adds extreme drag and reduces climb performance
High temperature
Lowers engine thrust and air density (less lift)
Full fuel
Increases weight to near or over limits
-------------
1.	 Takeoff May Fail Completely
		Aircraft may not reach Vr (rotation speed) within the available runway
		Could result in runway overrun, especially at shorter or high-altitude airports
	2.	 Extremely Poor Climb Rate
		Even if airborne, the aircraft might only climb a few hundred feet per minute or less
		Risk of hitting obstacles or terrain near airport
	3.	 Engine Overstress
		Engines will be operating near or at max thrust for longer than safe
		Overheating, wear, or even failure possible
	4.	 Stall Risk
		At low speeds and high weights, the aircraft is closer to stall margin
		Any turbulence or pilot input error can trigger aerodynamic stall
	5.	 Structural Damage
		Gear doors and flaps arent designed to handle cruise speeds
		Prolonged flight in this config can damage the landing gear, flap actuators, or wing structure

comments.text:
There are 2 serious points in the AI 171 Ahmedabad crash:

1 Fuel sabotage or engine failure? What if someone from the ground staff deliberately cut off the fuel supply to the engines? That would explain why the aircraft was able to taxi using leftover fuel in the pipelines but didnt get proper fuel from the main tank. As a result, both engines failed right after takeoffproven by the deployment of the RAT. This raises strong suspicion of sabotage on ground.

2 Pilots decision: The runway is 5 km long. Planes usually take off within 1 km, but this plane rolled till the very end and still couldnt lift off. That clearly means it wasnt getting enough thrust. If the pilot sensed low power, why continue the takeoff instead of aborting it? A rejected takeoff could have saved 
We need a full investigationincluding what happened on the ground before takeoff.

comments.text: The sound is the original video taken from the apartment is the sound of RAT (Ram Air Turbine)  which in the 787-8, deploys only when there is an electrical failure, hydraulic failure or a dual-engine failure. So there's a high chance that the engines were not producing thrust due to some issue. One more thing that 'garybpilot' explained in his video is that in the video taken from the apartment, the landing gears of the aircraft are tilted to the front. If you search up the landing gear retraction of a 787-8, you can see that the gears are first tilted to the front and then they are taken back into the bay. This could mean that the pilot had selected 'Gear Up' but due to an electrical failure, the gear retraction process could not complete and the gear stayed in that position. The theory that the first officer mistakenly changed the flaps setting instead of selecting the gear up lever is very unlikely in my opinion. If you look at the cockpit of a 787, you will notice that the flaps lever and the gear up lever and far apart for the first officer to mistakenly change the flaps setting and as well mentioned above there is high probability that the pilots had selected 'gear up' but it did not get completed due to some failure.
